The current custom exception handling (added by @pschella in PR #273) is nice for exposing custom exceptions to Python code, but a little bit cumbersome in declaration.  Unless I'm missing some existing simplification, it requires (copying from `example-custom-exceptions.cpp`):

```C++
    static py::exception<MyCppException> ex(m, "MyPythonException");
    py::register_exception_translator([](std::exception_ptr p) {
        try {
            if (p) std::rethrow_exception(p);
        } catch (const MyCppException &e) {
            PyErr_SetString(ex.ptr(), e.what());
        }
    });
```
This seems needlessly complex in the definition code: basically every definition is going to look exactly the same.  Would it not be possible to expose some other, simplified interface such as:

```C++
py::register_exception<CppException>(m, "PythonExceptionName");
```
that creates the internal static instance and registers the translator?  Even a macro, such as `PYBIND11_CUSTOM_EXCEPTION(CppException, PythonException, m)` would be considerably more convenient.  Of course I could write such a macro for my own code--but right now the custom exception definition seems to require a lot of what feels like implementation detail.

Granted the current code allows you to group multiple exceptions together, but that seems like a very minimal gain for the increased definition complexity.

